
Stereofidelic is a computer font, made from Typodermic Fonts. It's a retro 1980s typeface. This font was released in several Microsoft Windows Vista computers. The Stereofidelic font is also available for Macintosh computers for TrueType and PostScript. Stereofidelic is in its own family, Stereofidelic. The author of this font is Ray Larabie.[tpl]cite web|title=Stereofidelic Font on dafont.com|url=http://www.dafont.com/stereofidelic.font|work=dafont.com|publisher=Typodermic Fonts|accessdate=19 August 2011[/tpl][tpl]cite web|title=Stereofidelic - Free Font Download|url=http://www.urbanfonts.com/fonts/Stereofidelic.htm|work=urbanfonts|publisher=Ray Larabie|accessdate=19 August 2011[/tpl][tpl]cite web|title=Stereofidelic - MyFonts|url=http://new.myfonts.com/fonts/larabie/stereofidelic/|work=MyFonts|publisher=Larabie|accessdate=19 August 2011[/tpl] 

== Origin ==

The Stereofidelic font was found on the Sixties lounge record.[tpl]cite web|title=Stereofidelic - 1001Fonts.com|url=http://www.1001fonts.com/font_details.html?font_id=1174|work=1001Fonts.com|publisher=1001Fonts|accessdate=19 August 2011[/tpl] 

== Author ==

Ray Larabie (born 1970 in Ottawa, Ontario) is a designer of computer TrueType and OpenType fonts. Beginning in 1996, Larabie distributed his designs over the internet as freeware, operating as his own independent type foundry LarabieFonts.Cabarga, Leslie. Logo, Font, & Lettering Bible: A Comprehensive Guide to the Design, Construction, and Usage of Alphabets and Symbols. Cincinnati, OH: HOW Design, 2004. 237.

== Upper/Lower Case ==

The Stereofidelic font is mainly an upper-case font, but sometimes it can be altered to be lower-case.

